<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Releases Statement on `Incident' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Releases Statement on `Incident' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305141894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The political department of the Croatian Defense 
Ministry has issued a statement expressing sincere regret over 
an incident that took place at a Croatian Rights Party [HSP] 
promotional event in Siroki Brijeg. The ministry also says it 
is surprised by the insinuation, which links the ministry with 
the incident. We condemn all forms of violence and firmly deny 
any association with the events the HSP leadership is trying to 
use to compromise the state leadership of the Republic of 
Croatia and its Defense Ministry. 
  The short time that it took the HSP to present the incident 
as an attack on the Washington agreement and to say who is to 
blame -- without any evidence -- clearly shows that this media 
campaign is politically motivated, aimed at presenting the 
Croatian policy on Bosnia-Herzegovina as war-mongering and 
duplicituous. We hope that the implementation, in the near 
future, of the agreement signed between the Croat and 
Bosniak-Muslim people in Bosnia-Herzegovina will most 
effectively contradict all insinuation and slanders recently 
used to try to compromise the Defense Ministry and the Croatian 
leadership's policy on Bosnia-Herzegovina, the statement says. 
  The HSP claims in a statement issued today that the 
authorities in Herzegovina have banned an HSP promotional event 
in Capljina. As it now expects the other scheduled events to be 
banned, the HSP tour in Herzegovina is now cancelled, the 
statement says among other things. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

