<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hogg: External Borders `Must Not Be Touched' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hogg: External Borders `Must Not Be Touched' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305185794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0305185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mladen Bosnjak on a news conference by Douglas </F>
Hogg, Minister of State at the British Foreign Office, in 
Sarajevo on 3 May -- recorded; Hogg speaks in English with 
superimposed Serbo-Croatian translation] 
  [Text] [Bosnjak] My visit has focused on the 
implementation of the Washington Agreement and the work of the 
contact group, Douglas Hogg said. I am encouraged by the 
pragmatic views expressed by Mr. Silajdzic. From what I heard 
in Zagreb yesterday and in Sarajevo today, I can see that there 
is commitment to the implementation of the agreement. My 
impression is that the most important thing is to have a clear 
geographic delineation between the cantons. 
  There is no doubt that the Serb side is to be blamed for the 
current situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina but, despite that, it 
cannot be excluded from the negotiations. From my talks with 
Prime Minister Silajdzic I gathered that there are limits beyond 
which one cannot go, and the most important one concerns the 
external borders of Bosnia-Herzegovina. Those must not be 
touched, but there is still room for a much looser agreement on 
the relations between the Serbs on the one hand and the 
Muslim-Croat federation on the other. 
  It is important to stress that the contact group consists of 
those countries that have so far played the most significant 
role, and will continue to play it in the future. It is also 
important that Russia is also included, Hogg said, and added: 
  [Hogg] The contact group is engaged in two main tasks. The 
first is to achieve a cease-fire for a limited period, and the 
second is to try to find an agreement between the Bosniaks, the 
Croats, and the Serbs. I think that the engagement of the 
contact group is a big step ahead. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

