<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic Says Serbs `Disrespect' Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic Says Serbs `Disrespect' Ultimatum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305224794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2200 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305224794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic 
had a telephone conversation with U.S. President Bill Clinton's 
special envoy Charles Redman. Mr Redman informed Prime Minister 
Silajdzic on the arrival of a contact group in Sarajevo on 
Thursday, 5 May. The Bosnia-Herzegovina prime minister informed 
Redman that the negotiations have been brought into question 
because of the disrespect for the NATO and UN ultimatum on the 
withdrawal of the aggressor forces from around Gorazde. 
Silajdzic emphasized the aggressor forces did not withdraw to a 
distance of three km from Gorazde and did not withdraw their 
heavy artillery from the 20 km exclusion zone from the town 
center as demanded by the ultimatum. 

</TEXT>

