<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic, Akashi Discuss Issues in Pale </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic, Akashi Discuss Issues in Pale </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305202394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1855 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, 3 May (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the republic of Srpska, said in Pale today that the 
Serbian side has offered a truce in the Brcko area and added 
that the cease-fire would be implemented unilaterally, even if 
the Muslims refuse to accept it. [passage omitted] 
  "We also discussed the situation in Sarajevo and agreed on 
the need for the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] neutrality and 
restraint, and the warring sides' self-control. We included 
this in the discussion on a global cease-fire which the Serb 
side underlined as being in its interest -- something I also 
discussed with Haris Silajdzic," Akashi said. The UN secretary 
general's special envoy assessed today's talks as "a good basis 
for making progress in the peace process," adding that he 
thought "progress might be achieved in the near future." 
  In reply to a reporter's remark that the Muslim side is 
complaining about the presence of the Serbian militia in the 
Gorazde exclusion zone, Karadzic said that the United Nations 
will be controlling the militia and that UNPROFOR has already 
assumed responsibility for the job. This was confirmed by 
Yasushi Akashi. We agreed that the police will be performing 
its tasks under the supervision of UNPROFOR and our civilian 
police, Akashi explained. 
  Replying to questions about a recent armed clash between 
UNPROFOR and the republic of Srpska army near Tuzla, Akashi said 
that this incident was discussed in great detail. 
  "We presented our version of the event and heard the Serbian 
version, agreeing that similar situations should be avoided in 
the future and that things should be resolved at the local 
level," Akashi said. It was also agreed at the Pale meeting 
that members of UNPROFOR's British battalion -- who have been 
stranded in Rogatica for several days now -- should be allowed 
through to Gorazde under conditions acceptable to both sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54686 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu086_i_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-086 </AU>
