<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   AFP Reports Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    AFP Reports Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305152794 Paris AFP in English 1506 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0305152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, May 3 (AFP) -- UN envoy Yasushi Akashi 
called on Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic Tuesday [3 May] 
to allow UN observers into "critical areas," including the 
expected key flashpoint of Brcko, a UN spokesman said here. 
Akashi wants the monitors deployed to stabilize the conflict 
ahead of ceasefire talks, said Michael Williams, Akashi's 
spokesman, ahead of the UN envoy's meeting with Karadzic. 
  "Mr. Akashi will be pressing the point that it would be 
advisable to obtain an enhanced UNPROFOR observation in critical 
areas in order to stabilize the situation in anticipation of 
possible ceasefire negotiations," Williams said. 
  Brcko, in northeastern Bosnia, is thought to be the Serbs' 
next target after their standoff over Gorazde. Seizure of Brcko 
would widen a strategic corridor linking Serbia and Serb-held 
areas in northwestern Bosnia. 
  Akashi and UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) commander General 
Bertrand de Lapresle began talks with Karadzic during the 
afternoon in the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Pale, the TANJUG 
news agency reported late Tuesday afternoon. "We are hoping 
that something positive in that regard will come out of the 
meeting this afternoon," Williams added. Earlier in the day 
Akashi met Bosnian Government leaders in Sarajevo. 
  Several western sources have reported concentrations of Serb 
and Bosnian Moslem forces near Brcko. Military experts have 
predicted it would their next strategic target after Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54687 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu086_i_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-086 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army: Serbs `Planted' Arms in French Convoy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army: Serbs `Planted' Arms in French Convoy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305202894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0305202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The fact that the chetnik security services are 
aiming to discredit the international humanitarian organizations 
that deliver aid to the citizens of Sarajevo is confirmed by the 
latest case where they planted ammunition in a convoy of the 
French humanitarian organization Premiere Urgence. This is 
stated in a communique from the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army Press 
Center. 
  After stopping the French humanitarian convoy, the chetniks 
took the drivers and the convoy escorts to Hotel Srbija, and 
parked the trucks in front of it. The operation to plant the 
ammunition in the trucks was organized by Miso Mijatovic, chief 
of the chetnik security services in Ilidza. He supervised the 
following members of the aggressor's military police: Sasa 
Rodnik, Captain Branislav, Dragan Draskovic, Boban Djurkovic, 
Gavro Grubacic, and Zoran Subotic, who brought the ammunition 
from a military warehouse in Luzani, and planted it the same 
evening among the humanitarian packages. 
  In the morning the trucks were inspected in front of the 
organizer and the members of the humanitarian convoy, while the 
SRNA TV team was already on the scene, who filmed and later 
broadcast the alleged discovery of the crates with the 
ammunition. 
  This is contained in the statement by the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army Press Center. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

