Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aid Workers Held by Serbs Risk Death Penalty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aid Workers Held by Serbs Risk Death Penalty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305195794 Paris AFP in English 1854 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0305195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, May 3 (AFP) -- Three out of 11 French aid 
workers held by the Bosnian Serbs near Sarajevo risk the death 
penalty or jail terms of up to 20 years, a spokesman for the 
relief agency Premiere Urgence (First Aid) said on Tuesday. The 
11 members of Premiere Urgence were imprisoned in a Serb 
barracks at Lukavica, a suburb of the Bosnian capital Sarajevo, 
on April 8 after their aid convoy was intercepted and on Monday, 
three of them were indicted for transporting arms to the Bosnian 
Moslems. 
  Spokesman Pascale de Lomas said judicial investigation of 
the 
case against the three would likely end on May 8 and their trial 
would follow immediately. The eight others would be freed. The 
parents of the only woman in the group, Patricia Ettouati, said 
the 11 were being held in the same room and were in good health, 
but had lost weight because of "foul food". 
  The Bosnian Serbs first proposed swapping the aid workers 
for 
11 Serb doctors and nurses held in Sarajevo by the Moslems. 
  Premiere Urgence, which has been active in Bosnia 
transporting food parcels to Sarajevo with the agreement of the 
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, will send lawyers 
and observers from Amnesty International and the International 
Federation of Human Rights to the trial, to be staged in the 
Bosnian Serb capital of Pale. 
  French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe has called the arrest of 
the 11 "hostage-taking" and demanded their "immediate and 
unconditional" release. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

