<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Offer Unilateral Truce </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Offer Unilateral Truce </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305182194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1743 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0305182194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 3 May (TANJUG) -- President of the 
republic of Srpska Radovan Karadzic said in Pale today that the 
Serbian side had offered a truce in the Brcko region and added 
the truce would be implemented unilaterally, even if the Muslims 
did not accept it. Karadzic held over three hours of talks in 
Pale with Yasushi Akashi, the UN secretary general's special 
envoy, and after the talks expressed satisfaction with the 
outcome. 
  "This is a very good example of cooperation, for we achieved 
significant progress at the talks today. Primarily, we cleared 
some problematic aspects of the situation in Sarajevo, Gorazde, 
and Brcko," Karadzic told reporters. "We offered the Muslim 
side a truce in the Brcko area, and if they do not accept, it we 
shall implement it unilaterally. If the Muslims agree to the 
deployment of military observers on both sides in the Brcko 
region, it will be a good example of a preventative action aimed 
at ending the crisis," Karadzic said. 
  Yasushi Akashi said they agreed to continue work on the 
stabilization of the overall situation, in particular in 
Gorazde, in accordance with an agreement reached in Belgrade. 
  "We also discussed the events around Tuzla and Brcko, where 
some military movements have been registered," Akashi said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

