<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Continuing Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Continuing Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Miners To Continue Action </H4>

<F P=102> LD0405093094 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 0500 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A meeting of the Solidarity Hard-Coal Council has 
been held in Katowice. Solidarity Chairman Marian Krzaklewski 
took part in the meeting, which ended in the early hours of the 
morning. 
  [Correspondent Witold Orzech] The trade unionists have sent 
a 
letter to Trade and Industry Minister Marek Pol, registering 
their vote of no-confidence in the boards of all coal companies. 
They think that the boards are not coping with the current 
situation. The Miners Solidarity has also called on the minister 
to take measures aimed at removing the causes of conflicts and 
tensions in the mining industry. 
  The hard-coal miners' assessment of the agreement between 
their colleagues in the lignite-mining industry and the 
government was sceptical. They adopted a resolution that the 
strike at 16 hard-coal mines in Katowice province and three zinc 
and lead mines should continue. 
  Karol Luzniak, the hard-coal section chairman, announced 
that 
miners from several other mines will join the strike starting at 
0600. 
  Marian Krzaklewski expressed the hope that the national 
industrial action starting today will prove successful for both 
Solidarity and the government, that the strike will make the 
government understand that it should not aim at confrontation 
with the union. As a result, when the government finally comes 
to understand this, [Finance Minister] Mr. Kolodko will have not 
60 but 120 or more days of peace, Marian Krzaklewski said. He 
did not rule out the possibility of using the strike fund for 
payouts to strike participants. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

