<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic: Federation Still Offered to Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic: Federation Still Offered to Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0305184594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0305184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic 
today received Douglas Hogg, minister of state at the British 
Foreign Office. On this occasion Silajdzic said that a limited 
cease-fire could be significant for the resumption of 
negotiations. He stressed that the aggressor was buying time 
with his acts -- such as bringing in soldiers dressed in police 
uniforms in and around Gorazde, and settling its people in other 
people's houses. 
  We have established a federation of Bosniaks and the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Croats, and we are still offering the 
federation to those who want to live with us, Silajdzic said. 
  Asked by Hogg what kind of relations would be established 
with the Serbian entity in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Silajdzic said: 
Whatever kind of entity they choose, they can join the 
federation. However, we cannot allow the people of Banja Luka 
to not be able to return to their homes. The international 
community has to guarantee them this right. All this would 
imply that the Serbs will have relations with Serbia, but not to 
the disadvantage of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  We believe that the contact group has a lot to do. We are 
taking it seriously, and we think that it is important for all 
of us, Silajdzic added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

