<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Balladur Pact With Zieleniec </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Balladur Pact With Zieleniec </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205144994 Prague CTK in English 1400 GMT 2 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0205144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 2 (CTK) -- Czech Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec said today Prague espoused both the goals of the 
European stability and security pact and the apprehension that 
developments in Europe be not affected by tension between 
individual states over various problems, including ethnic 
minorities. 
  Speaking after a meeting with his Danish counterpart Niels 
Petersen, Zieleniec stressed the need to treat the pact most 
responsibly and cautiously. It is necessary to realize that 
ill-prepared moves can be "counterproductive" and that they 
could unleash processes leading to instability instead of 
stability. 
  The security and stability pact for Europe was submitted by 
French Premier Edouard Balladur in June 1993. It is designed to 
secure stability and security in Europe, to protect economic and 
trade interests of individual countries and to produce 
agreements on good neighborhood and respect for ethnic 
minorities's rights. The pact would be signed by European 
states, the United States and Canada. 
  Petersen said his government considered the pact a good and 
constructive idea. European countries need to solve some 
problems with their neighbors and this is a sort of 
"preventative diplomacy," he said. Admitting that this may not 
be easy, Petersen added the pact could be a valuable 
contribution to stability in Europe. He recalled that the 
conference on the pact is to open in Paris at the end of May and 
that the pact could be signed in Paris in the spring of 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

