<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa on European Stability, U.S. Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa on European Stability, U.S. Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0305204994 Warsaw PAP in English 1917 GMT 3 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0305204994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 3 -- President Lech Walesa on Tuesday 
told diplomatic corps accredited to Warsaw that a "real and full 
European integration has become possible thanks to the victory 
of democracy" in our continent. "The integration is favoured by 
such initiatives as the Partnership for Peace. Poland expresses 
the hope that it will become a road towards the creation of an 
efficient European security system," Walesa said at a meeting 
held at the royal castle on the occasion of the national day of 
Poland, the 3rd of May constitution anniversary. 
  "Regional cooperation also brings us closer to the united 
and 
safe Europe," Walesa stressed and added that Poland attaches 
importance to the Visegrad group and the Council of the Baltic 
Countries and the regional meeting at Litomysl. 
  The Polish president spoke of Poland's "frequent and 
significant contacts with Washington, and also Bonn, London and 
Paris" and said: "We are of the opinion that the role of the 
United States in maintaining European stability should not be 
weakened. At the same time we attach great weight to 
cooperation with democratic Russia. Our proposal to codify the 
principles of the Eastern policy serves this end. Through 
discussions with our partner we are trying to open the road 
towards concrete solutions." 
  Apart from President Walesa and his wife Danuta, the meeting 
was hosted by Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak, Sejm Speaker Jozef 
Oleksy, Senate Speaker Adam Struzik and Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski. On behalf of the diplomats the dean of the 
Diplomatic Corps, Papal Nuncio Archbishop Jozef Kowalczyk 
expressed recognition to the Polish president and the Polish 
people for their "everyday toil and struggle for a new shape of 
the democratic country." 

</TEXT>

