<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Decline Reported Slowing Down </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Decline Reported Slowing Down </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94CH0232B Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY in Czech 29 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> 94CH0232B </F>
<F P=104>  Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by unnamed Bratislava correspondent: "Close of Last </F>
Year Confirms Decline Is Slowing Down"] 
  [Text] Bratislava--Some macroeconomic indicators of the 
Slovak Republic [SR] at the close of last year show that the 
dynamic of the economic decline is slowing down. According to 
the monetary analysis of the Slovak National Bank [SNB] with 
preliminary data for December 1993, the GDP, which in the first 
and second quarters of 1993 reduced its lag behind the 
comparable periods in 1992 from 5.5 percent to 5 percent, cut 
this difference in the third quarter to 4.3 percent and in the 
last quarter to 4.1 percent. Of the total yearly inflation of 
25.1 percent, the largest portion--more than 
two-fifths--originated in the first quarter (11.7 percent), 
whereas, in the last three months, only one-eighth did (monthly 
values declined from 1.4 percent to 0.6 percent). 
  Semiannual comparisons of quarterly and monthly values of 
industrial production showed a slowing down of the decline from 
16.6 percent in the first quarter to 13.5 percent in the third 
quarter, and to 12.6 percent in October, 8.8 percent in 
November, and 7.9 percent in December. 
  In the course of the year, unemployment has been increasing 
roughly by 0.5 percent per quarter. The balance of foreign trade 
went from a surplus of hundreds of millions of Slovak korunas 
[Sk] to a deficit of billions, while turnover increased (Sk66.3 
billion in the first quarter, 85.4 billion in the second, 100.7 
billion in the third, and 67.7 billion in October and November). 
  Foreign currency reserves of the banking system doubled to 
$1.4 billion, while the NSB reserves increased from 0.2 to 0.5 
billion. Gross foreign debt kept growing until the third quarter 
(from $2.4 to $3 billion) but has remained steady since then. 
  The deficit of the state budget deepened especially in the 
first quarter (debit balance Sk11 billion) and last month 
(difference of 7 billion), and during 1993 registered a total of 
Sk23 billion. The total debt of the government (excluding 
foreign loans) thus approached Sk60 billion toward the end of 
the year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

