<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Approaches Court on UN Corridor Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Approaches Court on UN Corridor Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505125994 Sofia BTA in English 1240 GMT 5 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0505125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, May 5 (BTA) -- The government today asked 
the Constitutional Court to rule on its powers to sanction the 
transit and temporary stay in Bulgaria of equipment of foreign 
states, government spokesman Raycho Raykov told journalists. 
  The issue of foreign troops transit is regulated by the 
Constitution which empowers the National Assembly to take the 
respective decisions. However, the Constitution makes no 
provisions about the transit of foreign military aircraft and 
vessels. This is regulated by the Civil Aviation Act and the 
Sea Space Act authorizing the Council of Ministers. However, 
the government's decision to allow a UN convoy of equipment for 
peacekeepers in Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM] this April provoked heated debates in 
parliament and the MP's came out with a declaration saying that 
only they could issue such permissions. 
  The Constitutional Court is expected to rule on this issue 
within three months, the government spokesman said. The 
government has assigned experts of the Ministry of the Interior, 
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Defence Ministry and of the 
Transport Ministry as well as of the Legal Department of the 
Council of Ministers to draft within two weeks temporary 
regulations for issuing such permissions until the passing of a 
final legislative decision on this issue. There are eight notes 
requesting transit permissions, the government spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

