<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Free Democrats' Peto Addresses Campaign Rally </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Free Democrats' Peto Addresses Campaign Rally </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505125394 Budapest MTI in English 2024 GMT 4 May 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0505125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 4 May (MTI) -- The Alliance of Free 
Democrats (SZDSZ) wishes to take part in the next government as 
a strong party, so as to be able to enforce its own programme, 
SZDSZ Chairman Ivan Peto told a Budapest rally tonight. The 
Free Democrats are not prepared to play "second fiddle" in the 
government. They hope that the new government to be formed 
after the May parliamentary elections will rely more on 
expertise, Peto said. 
  In his view, the governing coalition can be dismissed not 
only by the Socialist Party but also by the liberal bloc 
composed of the SZDSZ, the Federation of Young Democrats, the 
Entrepreneurs' Party, and the Agrarian Association. 
  Campaign manager Balint Magyar said that the election 
campaign is harsher now than it was four years ago. This 
harshness is reflected mainly by certain programmes aired by the 
state radio and television. In reply to a question, Peto said 
that, should the Free Democrats come to power, they would not 
intervene in the internal affairs of the two media. The deputy 
presidents of the state radio and television would be dismissed, 
not for political reasons, but because they have proved 
themselves unfit for managing the public service media in an 
unbiased way. 

</TEXT>

