<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   UP's Bugaj on Presidential Race, Candidates </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UP's Bugaj on Presidential Race, Candidates </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0405140394 Warsaw Radio Zet in Polish 0620 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0405140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Zet </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Ryszard Bugaj, chairman of Union of Labor, </F>
by Andrzej Woyciechowski at the Radio Zet studio in Warsaw on 
the "Guest of Radio Zet" program--live] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Woyciechowski] Let us go 
back for a moment to the political nature of these strikes. Do 
you think the political nature of the strikes is associated with 
the coming presidential election, or is it perhaps still too 
early? 
  [Bugaj] You know, I do not think so. At any rate, I think 
that, so far, the president has been acting with some restraint. 
I have had the opportunity in the past to voice views in this 
very studio that were critical of the president, but, regarding 
this conflict, I must say he has been demonstrating restraint.... 
  [Woyciechowski, interrupting] Will you vote for Walesa in 
the presidential election? 
  [Bugaj] I do not think so. I hope there will be a 
countercandidate for whom I could vote.... 
  [Woyciechowski, interrupting] And what kind of candidate 
would it have to be? Let us not give specific names. 
  [Bugaj] You know, I would put it this way--and you are right 
about not mentioning any names. Whether he would be someone of 
left-wing or right-wing views--that is rather irrelevant to me, 
or at least I see that as a secondary issue. But, of course, I 
would like him to be someone who respects the Constitution very 
much, who is capable of resolving situations relevant to the 
president, and who is capable of being an umpire and of enjoying 
strong authority. But I must say I would prefer this person not 
to have very strong views because it might happen that he will 
have to cooperate with very different types of government, of a 
very different nature, with very different [words indistinct] 
  [Woyciechowski, interrupting] Do you know of such a person? 
Is there anyone like that in Poland? 
  [Bugaj] You know, I know an enormous number of such people, 
indeed, but the problem is that none of those figures are 
distinguished or outstanding enough to be able to take up the 
post without problems. I think there are such people in the 
Freedom Union [UW], and perhaps I could find them in our party, 
too. I would not hesitate to say there are also such people at 
the very right-wing end of the political scene. I think the 
most important matter is that we shape the Constitution in a way 
that would prevent the presidency from becoming something like 
the chief executive office, or something of that nature 
because.... 
  [Woyciechowski, interrupting] And can I ask you to give a 
name now? 
  [Bugaj] You know, what I think is that, for instance, when 
it comes to the UW, both Tadeusz Mazowiecki and Jacek Kuron are 
the kinds of people who fulfill my criteria, and when it comes 
to our circles, both Karol Modzelewski and, for instance, 
Aleksander Malachowski fulfill the criteria. Which does not 
mean that they want or are able to run--that is a separate 
issue. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

