<H3> <TI>   UK's Hogg Meets Serbian Leaders in Belgrade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK's Hogg Meets Serbian Leaders in Belgrade </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hogg Comments on Kosovo </H4>

<F P=102> LD0505114094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1103 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0505114094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pristina, 5 May (TANJUG) -- Douglas Hogg, minister 
of state in the UK Foreign Office, said in Pristina today that 
both the British Government and the international community are 
of the view that the issue of the rights of Albanians of Kosovo 
and Metohija will have to be resolved within the borders of 
Serbia. I wish to say that Kosovo is part of Serbia and we do 
not believe that the borders should be changed. We also think 
that there is no need for an independent state on the territory 
of Kosovo, Douglas Hogg told journalists, following his talks 
with Milos Savovic, governor [nacelnik] of the Kosovo district. 
The main tasks are to find ways of implementing the political, 
cultural, and civil rights of the Albanian community in Kosovo 
and to allow the Albanians to play a full role in political and 
administrative life, Hogg said. 
  The British minister of state continued his visit by talking 
to ethnic Albanian representatives in Pristina. 

</TEXT>

