<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK Ready To Resume Talks With Croatia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSK Ready To Resume Talks With Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0405201594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1916 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0405201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 4 May (TANJUG) -- Milan Babic, foreign 
minister of the republic of Serb Krajina [RSK], conveyed to 
Geert Ahrens, deputy cochairman of the Conference on the Former 
Yugoslavia, the Serb side's readiness to continue negotiations 
on the normalization of relations between the RSK and Croatia. 
  Babic said that the RSK proposed Turanj or Geneva as a site 
for the negotiations. We believe that it is necessary to 
conduct negotiations in a place that is not beset by political 
tensions, so we suggest Turanj, a place under the control of the 
UN peace force in the buffer zone where peace has already been 
restored, Babic said in a statement to Politika TV. 
  He stressed that Turanj is accessible to both 
representatives 
of the RSK and the Croatian Government -- something that is an 
extra advantage given the fact that at this stage of 
negotiations frequent meetings of technical and expert groups 
would be needed. 
  Babic also says that the Serb side was today presented with 
a 
document by the Conference on the Former Yugoslavia, headlined 
"The Program of Economic Affairs," although it was not discussed 
since today's meeting was by and large focused on the question 
of when and where these negotiations were going to take place. 
  Following the meeting Ahrens said that the atmosphere at the 
talks with the RSK foreign minister was excellent and that the 
talks would resume next week. 
  Ahrens added that the Croatian side was also completely 
ready 
to resume negotiations and that some minor details had yet to be 
decided upon prior to the second phase of negotiations. 

</TEXT>

