<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Holds Talks With UK's Hurd </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Holds Talks With UK's Hurd </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505193694 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1900 
GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0505193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd arrived today 
for a two-day visit to the Czech Republic. He met Prime 
Minister Vaclav Klaus in the late afternoon. Lucie Weissova has 
more details. 
  [Weissova] After the meeting, Douglas Hurd told journalists 
that the talks dealt with Europe's future, with the expansion of 
European institutions, in particular the European Union and the 
North Atlantic Alliance. The two politicians agreed that a 
unified Europe should not become a superstate with Brussels as 
its capital. Rather, it should be a union of independent states 
that should be helped by this organization in efficient 
cooperation. 
  Vaclav Klaus handed the British foreign secretary a personal 
letter inviting Prime Minister John Major to visit the Czech 
Republic. 
  Responding to a question as to whether the Czech Republic 
could become a member of the European Union before the year 
2000, Douglas Hurd said: 
  [Begin Hurd recording in English with superimposed Czech 
translation] That is up to you. You initiate and you choose 
gradual steps. The debate and the negotiations will follow. I 
can only say that it is well possible. However, the initiative 
rests with you. [end recording] 
  [Weissova] According to Vaclav Klaus, the Czech Republic 
will 
certainly submit the European Union membership application 
before 1996, when the EU conference on institutional reform will 
take place. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54864 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu088_c_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hurd Received by Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hurd Received by Foreign Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0605113594 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1000 
GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0605113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In conclusion of his two-day visit to the Czech 
Republic, UK Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd has met with his 
Czech counterpart Josef Zieleniec. Klara Stejskalova reports: 
  [Stejskalova] The talks between the foreign ministers 
chiefly 
concerned the Czech Republic's membership in the European 
economic and security structures. Minister Zieleniec praised 
Britain's role in involving the countries of Central Europe in 
the European Union. At the same time, he stressed that we are 
striving for membership not because we want to be recipients of 
European aid but because we want to contribute to transformation 
using our own funds. According to Hurd, the European Union must 
grow gradually, on the basis of agreements that have already 
been concluded. 
  The talks also concerned NATO and the Partnership for Peace 
program. The two ministers praised the role of the United 
States, saying that its military presence in Europe is the 
guarantee of stability and that it has played an important part 
in the recent changes in Central Europe. 

</TEXT>

