<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic Demands Akashi Resignation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505142594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0505142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] We were hoping that this evening we would discuss 
the continuation of the peace process with the contact group -- 
[word indistinct] that the chetniks would have withdrawn from 
Gorazde in accordance with the ultimatum. This was stated today 
by Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic. 
Unfortunately the chetniks have not withdrawn. Second, it is 
(unacceptable) that the United Nations should make arrangements 
with the aggressor's representatives, and help them transport 
their tanks from one location to another so that they can go on 
killing civilians somewhere else. That is why we will demand 
today that Yasushi Akashi tenders his resignation, Haris 
Silajdzic added. The decision to demand Akashi's resignation 
was made today at the session of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Presidency. This demand will be presented to the contact group, 
which is to arrive in Sarajevo this evening to revive the peace 
process. 

</TEXT>

