<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Observers To Be Deployed at Brcko </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Observers To Be Deployed at Brcko </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505161894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1455 GMT 5 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0505161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brcko, 5 May (TANJUG) -- Seven UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] observers will monitor the confrontations at 
the Brcko front from Saturday, 7 May. They will be joined by 
another nine UNPROFOR members on Sunday. This is the result of 
the talks held today between Sergio de Mello, the UN deputy 
special envoy for civilian affairs and Nikola Koljevic, the 
vice-president of the Bosnian Serb Republic. The military 
delegations were led by Dutch Colonel Jup and commander of the 
[Serbian] East Bosnia Corps Gen Novica Simic. 
  The observers on the Serb side will be deployed at four 
points in Brcko and will be able to communicate with their 
fellow observers who will be deployed on the Muslim side. Our 
main objective is to prevent confrontations around Brcko and, 
following the Gorazde crisis, to prevent crises in general, 
Sergio de Mello told reporters. We want to show that we do not 
want war and that everything can be resolved through political 
negotiation, Koljevic said. 
  The result of the talks today was also that the commander of 
the [Serbian] East-Bosnia Corps Maj-Gen Novica Simic and the 
commander of the [Muslim] Second Corps Nazim Sadic will most 
probably meet soon. 
  They will try to agree on a cease-fire, to put into practice 
the agreement reached by Radovan Karadzic and Yasushi Akashi, it 
was said at the press conference. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

