<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crvenkovski Denies `Vance Plan' for Republic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crvenkovski Denies `Vance Plan' for Republic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505172794 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0505172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Second Phase of Negotiations to </F>
Start"] 
  [Text] Upon his return from New York and Brussels, 
Macedonian [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] 
Foreign Minister Stevo Crvenkovski refuted any reports of an 
alleged "Vance plan" for resolving the Greek-Macedonian dispute. 
"We have worked together these past few weeks with Cyrus Vance 
and Matthew Nemitz on a possible solution for the dispute, but 
no final agreement has been reached thus far," Crvenkovski 
stated. "We expect the second phase of the negotiations to 
start in about 10 days or to reach some kind of an agreement in 
the meantime." He expressed hope Cyrus Vance's efforts would 
eventually result in reviving of the talks. 
  In regard to his meetings with various U.S. officials, 
Crvenkovski said they have shown clear support of the 
independence and territorial integrity of Macedonia and all that 
is achieved by this small state in the course of the past two 
years. He also pointed out the entire media in the United 
States wrote in favor of Macedonia during his visit, condemning 
at the same time the Greek embargo and behavior. 
  He said his meeting with the Western European Union 
President 
[WEU] van Ekkelen proved very useful. Besides discussing the 
situation in the region, they have agreed in principle to 
establish various kinds of cooperation between the WEU and 
Macedonia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

