<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cuba Releases Dissident as `Gesture' Toward SR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cuba Releases Dissident as `Gesture' Toward SR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0605113894 Bratislava REPUBLIKA in Slovak 4 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0605113894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava REPUBLIKA </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "bj": "Martinez Set Free; Cuban Charge d'Affairs </F>
on Yesterday's Demonstration"] 
  [Text] Bratislava--"This is a needless politicization and 
ideologization of the problem, which cannot have a positive 
influence on bilateral relations between Slovakia and Cuba," 
Juan Sanchez Monroe, charge d'affairs at the Cuban Embassy in 
the Slovak Republic, told a news conference about yesterday's 
demonstration for the release from prison of dissident Joel 
Duenas Martinez, which was organized by the Bratislava branch of 
Amnesty International. Out of respect for the Slovak public and 
following a personal conversation with Marta Simeckova, the 
Bratislava representative of Amnesty International, J.S. Monroe, 
pledged already last year that he would personally plead for the 
revision of the verdict. This happened in March of this year 
and in April Martinez was released from prison. "Cuba did this 
as a friendly gesture toward the Slovak Republic," J.S. Monroe 
said. That is why he considers yesterday's demonstration, as 
well as the previous March demonstration, inappropriate 
interference in the Slovak-Cuban dialogue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

