<H3> <TI>   Strikes Continuing; Negotiations Stalled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Strikes Continuing; Negotiations Stalled </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Walesa Sees Threat to State </H4>

<F P=102> LD0605085494 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 0700 
GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0605085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Presidential Spokesman Andrzej Drzycimski has said 
that, according to President Lech Walesa, the current wave of 
strikes may hinder the functioning of the state. The president 
thinks that serious negotiations between the government and 
trade unionists should prevent any further strikes or stop them 
altogether. 
  [Begin Drzycimski recording] This strike, which is beginning 
to affect key security industries, is a threat not only to a 
particular industry but also to the whole state. That is why 
the president is saying that one must consider whether all of 
the industries should strike when this could bring a halt to the 
whole country. This strike is not aimed at changing political 
power but at finding economic solutions. The president thinks 
that, in such a situation, the talks must be continued because 
nothing can happen without them. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Andrzej Drzycimki said that the president has 
not 
yet decided on the excess wage increase tax [neopopiwek] law 
because he has received contradictory opinions on this 
regulation. Lech Walesa thinks that opponents as well as 
supporters of the excess wage increase tax have very valid 
arguments. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

