<H3> <TI>   Election Results, Reactions Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Election Results, Reactions Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Fidesz Chairman `Willing' To Resign </H4>

<F P=102> LD0905010694 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
0000 GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0905010694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Viktor Orban, chairman of the Federation of Young 
Democrats [Fidesz], has announced that he is willing to give up 
his mandate as party chairman but will remain in his post if the 
Young Democrats' congress asks him to do so. Fidesz, which 
according to the most recent data is the last--sixth, with 
scarcely more than 7 percent of the votes--of the parties to get 
into parliament, will make a decision at a session of the 
presidium tomorrow about the convening and date of this 
extraordinary meeting. 
  Viktor Orban said that as long as he is chairman of Fidesz 
his party would certainly not enter into a coalition with the 
Hungarian Socialist Party, which received the most votes. 
According to Orban, the country has voted for a radical change; 
Fidesz, however, wanted only a partial turnabout, and this is 
probably why it performed more poorly than expected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54940 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu089_h_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Election Results, Reactions Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Election Results, Reactions Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Orban Not Planning To Resign </H4>

<F P=102> LD0905122894 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1000 GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0905122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Viktor Orban [chairman of the Federation of Young 
Democrats -- Fidesz] has been misunderstood; he does not want to 
resign. Katalin Horvath reports: 
  [Horvath] The country does not want what the Fidesz wants. 
Probably we could not explain well enough and could not convince 
people of the ideas of the Fidesz. This was the cause of our 
poor performance, said Fidesz Chairman Viktor Orban. 
  As a matter of fact, the Hungarian election result resembles 
a Polish scenario. It means that the government party could not 
cope with the economy and people cast their votes for the party 
which ruled before 1990. The Fidesz has been working for one 
and a half years to prevent this -- unfortunately, without 
success. 
  The Fidesz will continue to be in opposition. If necessary, 
in the second round, Fidesz candidates will step back in favor 
of the Alliance of Free Democrats. By doing so at least the 
Hungarian Socialist Party's advantage can be reduced even though 
it cannot be changed, Viktor Orban said. 
  Speaking about his chairmanship, he merely said that his 
statement of last night had been misunderstood. He is not even 
thinking of resigning. The party congress will decide on his 
chairmanship. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

