<H3> <TI>   Election Results, Reactions Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Election Results, Reactions Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Unofficial Final Results' Reported </H4>

<F P=102> LD0905024194 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
0200 GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0905024194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As it was four years ago, Hungary will again have a 
parliament with six parties, and it will include the same 
parties as in 1990. However, their positions of power will be 
considerably different. 
  According to the unofficial final results of the first round 
in the parliamentary elections, the Hungarian Socialist Party is 
in first place with 32.4 percent of the votes; the Alliance of 
Free Democrats is second with 19.4 percent; the Hungarian 
Democratic Forum is in third place with 12 percent of the votes, 
followed by the Independent Smallholders Party with 8.5 percent. 
The Federation of Young Democrats ended up in fifth place with 
7.4 percent. The Christian Democratic People's Party obtained 
(?7.3) percent of the votes. 
  The other nine parties fielding national lists did not 
achieve the 5 percent necessary to enter parliament. 

</TEXT>

