<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Election Results, Reactions Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    SZDSZ's Kuncze Interviewed </H4>

<F P=102> LD0905121594 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
0445 GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0905121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Studio interview with Gabor Kuncze, Alliance of Free </F>
Democrats nominee for prime minister, by correspondent Judit 
Laszlo; date not given -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Laszlo] Are you satisfied with the election 
results? 
  [Kuncze] The SZDSZ [Alliance of Free Demmocrats has done 
well 
in these elections. We received more than 1 million votes on 
the lists. In effect, this means that we repeated our 1990 
election results, that is we have achieved the aim we had set 
for ourselves. The SZDSZ is the only party which has a chance 
of preventing a landslide victory by the Hungarian Socialist 
Party and of preventing the continuance of a covert one-party 
system after the May elections. We have to wait for the results 
of the second round. [passage omitted] 
  [Laszlo] There is an agreement between the SZDSZ and the 
Federation of Young Democrats [Fidesz] that candidates who 
scored poorly are to step down in favor of the other party's 
candidate. Having seen the Fidesz results, do you think that is 
going to happen? Will the Fidesz candidates step down in favor 
of the SZDSZ? 
  [Kuncze] The Fidesz leaders have stated several times that 
they respect the agreement. The SZDSZ has also said this. 
Therefore, I am sure that this agreement will work. I also add 
that the same is true of the Agrarian Alliance and the Liberal 
Civic Alliance-Entrepreneurs' Party. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

