<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Solidarity Seeks Two-Way Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Solidarity Seeks Two-Way Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0805190494 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1730 GMT 8 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0805190494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Relayed by TV Polonia Network] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Solidarity Mining and Power Industry 
Secretariat has decided during its meeting in Katowice to ask 
the government for immediate and direct talks with the union. 
Otherwise the union plans to intensify the protest action and 
restart the strike in brown coal mines. 
  Strike committees of the hard and brown coal mining 
industries and power and heating industries took part in today's 
meeting of the Mining and Power Industry Secretariat in 
Katowice. Solidarity leader Marian Krzaklewski also took part 
in this meeting. After the failed culmination of the strike 
last Friday [6 May], which was announced by Krzaklewski, the 
trade unionists were discussing how the Solidarity protests 
would be organized in the next few days. 
  Solidarity is not withdrawing its general demands but is now 
willing to agree to talk about the power industry demands on the 
condition that these would be two-way talks between Solidarity 
and the government. [passage omitted] 
  It is possible that a meeting between Marian Krzaklewski and 
Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak or President Lech Walesa may 
still take place tonight after the premiere of the Kazimierz 
Kutz film in Katowice. 

</TEXT>

